{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640953"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17849"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17849"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.47,0.16,0.26,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77666"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10563"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17849"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63179"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5099"},{"type":"tags","id":"10063"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24632"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77666"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about the regulation of glucose oxidation and availability of other substrates is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Products of fatty acid oxidation feedback activate glucose oxidation","Acetyl-CoA levels activate pyruvate dehydrogenase","Hormonal control of glucose oxidation is centred around phosphofructokinase regulation","Insulin increases pyruvate dehydrogenase activity","Citrate activation of phosphofructokinase is a well-characterised mechanism"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsulin increases pyruvate dehydrogenase activity\u003C/strong\u003E, which promotes glucose oxidation by facilitating the conversion of pyruvate to acetyl-CoA. This is a key regulatory step in glucose metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProducts of fatty acid oxidation\u003C/strong\u003E actually inhibit glucose oxidation through the Randle cycle, where increased levels of acetyl-CoA and NADH inhibit pyruvate dehydrogenase, reducing glucose oxidation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetyl-CoA\u003C/strong\u003E inhibits pyruvate dehydrogenase, not activates it. This inhibition decreases glucose oxidation when fatty acid oxidation is high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHormonal control\u003C/strong\u003E of glucose oxidation involves multiple enzymes, including pyruvate dehydrogenase and glycogen synthase, not just phosphofructokinase (PFK).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECitrate\u003C/strong\u003E actually inhibits phosphofructokinase, decreasing glycolysis and glucose oxidation. This is part of the feedback mechanism to regulate energy production based on cellular needs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Insulin increases pyruvate dehydrogenase (PDH) activity, promoting glucose oxidation.","Acetyl-CoA inhibits pyruvate dehydrogenase, reducing glucose oxidation."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":